<subSubSection id="C37A6522FFF9FFDC09F6883AFAE558BE" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDF36A9FFF9FFDC09F6883AFAE558BE" blockId="12.[151,1436,1867,2036]" lastBlockId="13.[153,1436,151,428]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B914EABBFFF9FFDD09F6883AFEC05F99" bold="true" box="[197,319,1903,1928]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Massive or thickly encrusting 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D2AFFF9FFDD0BAF883AFCD95F96" box="[668,806,1903,1927]" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Ancorinidae</taxonomicName>
with a thin, indistinct non-detachable ectosome defined by pigmented cells and aquiferous canals. Megascleres include oxeas in several size categories, and triaenes of different 
<typeStatus id="54DB880BFFF9FFDD083488ECFEBD5FC0" box="[263,322,1977,2001]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">types</typeStatus>
including dichotriaenes, plagiotriaenes, anatriaenes, and protriaenes. Bundles of megascleres radiate strictly in the outer choanosome, expanding into brushes at the surface, and extending beyond. Microscleres include small euasters, and acanthomicrorhabds which form a dermal crust (emended from 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF14B58FFF8FFDC0DAA8FC2FAF058BE" author="Uriz" box="[1177,1295,151,175]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Uriz, M. J. (2002) Family Ancorinidae Schmidt, 1870. In: Hooper, J. N. A. &amp; van Soest, R. W. M. (Eds.) Systema Porifera: A guide to the classification of sponges. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers Ltd, New York, pp. 108 - 126." type="book chapter" year="2002">
Uriz 
<number id="3DA8248EFFF8FFDC0DE18FC2FAF058BE" box="[1234,1295,151,175]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37A6522FFF8FFDC09F68FE9FDE159BD" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BDF36A9FFF8FFDC09F68FE9FDE159BD" blockId="13.[153,1436,151,428]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="B914EABBFFF8FFDC09F68FE9FEC658C5" bold="true" box="[197,313,188,212]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Remarks.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus id="54DB880BFFF8FFDC084F8FE8FE5358C4" box="[380,428,189,213]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D2AFFF8FFDC0B268FE8FD0F58C5" box="[533,752,189,212]" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Ecionemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="acervus">
<emphasis id="B914EABBFFF8FFDC0B268FE8FD0F58C5" box="[533,752,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ecionemia acervus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was first described from 
<collectingCountry id="F3777639FFF8FFDC0D148FE9FBB158C5" box="[1063,1102,188,212]" name="Fiji" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fiji</collectingCountry>
and has a wide distribution throughout the Indo-Pacific. The megascleres are large oxeas (&gt; 
<number id="3DA8248EFFF8FFDC0AB68F8AFC4158E6" box="[901,958,223,247]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1000.0">1000</number>
um), orthotriaenes, and anatriaenes. The microscleres are acanthomicrorhabds, chiasters, and tylasters. In her diagnosis of the genus, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF14B58FFF8FFDC0D918E51FAD9590D" author="Uriz" box="[1186,1318,260,284]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Uriz, M. J. (2002) Family Ancorinidae Schmidt, 1870. In: Hooper, J. N. A. &amp; van Soest, R. W. M. (Eds.) Systema Porifera: A guide to the classification of sponges. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers Ltd, New York, pp. 108 - 126." type="book chapter" year="2002">
Uriz (
<number id="3DA8248EFFF8FFDC0DD08E51FAE1590D" box="[1251,1310,260,284]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2002.0">2002</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
states that the euasters of 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D2AFFF8FFDC08788E7CFE3C5951" box="[331,451,297,320]" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Ecionemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B914EABBFFF8FFDC08788E7CFE3C5951" box="[331,451,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ecionemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are never oxyasters, but 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D2AFFF8FFDC0BDA8E7CFCB35951" box="[745,844,296,320]" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Ecionemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="densa">
<emphasis id="B914EABBFFF8FFDC0BDA8E7CFCB35951" box="[745,844,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">E. densa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has oxyasters in the smallest euaster category (see Table 
<number id="3DA8248EFFF8FFDC09D38E19FF0F5975" box="[224,240,332,356]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="3.0">3</number>
). It appears that species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D2AFFF8FFDC0B018E18FD555975" box="[562,682,333,356]" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Ecionemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B914EABBFFF8FFDC0B018E18FD555975" box="[562,682,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ecionemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
never have the larger category of oxyasters that are found in the choanosome of 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D2AFFF8FFDC087A8E25FE4E5999" box="[329,433,368,392]" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Ancorina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B914EABBFFF8FFDC087A8E25FE4E5999" box="[329,433,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ancorina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. and 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D2AFFF8FFDC0B288E25FD755999" box="[539,650,368,392]" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Stryphnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B914EABBFFF8FFDC0B288E25FD755999" box="[539,650,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Stryphnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. Note also, that the euasters in 
<collectingCountry id="F3777639FFF8FFDC0D208E25FB575996" box="[1043,1192,367,391]" name="New Zealand" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D2AFFF8FFDC0C178E24FA645999" box="[1316,1435,369,392]" class="Demospongiae" family="Ancorinidae" genus="Ecionemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astrophorida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B914EABBFFF8FFDC0C178E24FA645999" box="[1316,1435,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ecionemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have recurved tips (see 
<figureCitation id="135B2A2CFFF8FFDC08928EC1FE1D59BD" box="[417,482,404,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1376,1399]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1355]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,193,1355]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 5. Megascleres and microscleres of New Zealand species of Ecionemia: Ecionemia alata, NIWA 52981: A. plagiotriaene, scale = 500 µm; B – C. anatriaenes, scale = 100 µm; D. chiaster with recurved spines, scale = 5 µm; E. acanthomicrorhabd, scale = 5 µm. Ecionemia novaezealandiae, NIWA 62156: F. plagiotriaene, scale = 500 µm; G. anatriaene, scale = 100 µm; H. promesotriaene, scale = 100 µm; I. chiaster with recurved spines, scale = 5 µm; J. spherochiaster, scale = 5 µm; K. acanthomicrorhabd, scale = 5 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282358/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number id="3DA8248EFFF8FFDC08E78EC1FE1D59BD" box="[468,482,404,428]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
D, I).
</paragraph>
